<html xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xml:lang="en"
      lang="en" metal:use-macro="context/@@main_template/master"
      i18n:domain="launchpad">

<body>

<metal:leftportlets fill-slot="portlets_one">
  <div class="portlet">
    <h4>Translating Applications:</h4>

    <div class="portletBody portletContent" i18n:translate="rosetta-blurb">
      <a i18n:attributes="title" title="Rosetta"
         href="rosetta" i18n:translate="">Rosetta</a> is a
      <b>web-based translation portal</b>.
      If your application uses the open source standard <i>gettext</i>
      system for software internationalisation, then you can easily have
      users contribute translations for your software through Rosetta.
      You simply upload the existing translations, point your community
      at Rosetta and then download their translations before you make
      your release. <a i18n:attributes="title" title="Rosetta"
      href="rosetta" i18n:translate="">Translate now!</a>
    </div>
  </div>
  
  <div class="portlet">
    <h4>Open Source People:</h4>

    <div class="portletBody portletContent">
      See what 
      <a href="/people/">people and teams</a> are registered in the
      Launchpad, which projects they are hacking or translating, and where
      they have been active in recent days.
    </div>
  </div>
</metal:leftportlets>

<metal:rightportlets fill-slot="portlets_two">
  <div class="portlet">
    <h4>Tracking Bugs:</h4>

    <div class="portletBody portletContent" i18n:translate="malone-blurb">
      <a i18n:attributes="title" title="Malone"
         href="malone" i18n:translate="">Malone</a> is a
      <b>web-based global bug tracking</b>
      tool. It is designed to track bugs across the whole open source
      process: it understands that the same code is re-used upstream
      and in different distributions, and allows us to have a single
      bug number for any bug, and track where it has been fixed and
      where it is still a problem. <a i18n:attributes="title" title="Malone"
      href="malone" i18n:translate="">Track bugs now!</a>
  </div>
</div>
</metal:rightportlets>

<div metal:fill-slot="main">

  <h1 i18n:translate="">Welcome to The Launchpad!</h1>

  <p i18n:translate="">The Launchpad is a collection of services for
    projects in the open source universe. You can register your
    project, and collaborate with the open source community on translations,
    bug squashing and the code you write.
  </p>

  <form action="/products/" method="get">
    <table>
      <tr>
        <td>
          <input name="text" size="30" />
          <input type="submit" value="Search" />
        </td>
      </tr>
    </table>
    <p class="formHelp">
      Use this form to find an open source application. Enter any part of
      the application name, title or description, and click "Search".
    </p>

  </form>

  <h2>Most Active Projects</h2>

  <p>The following projects are making the most active use of Launchpad
  services (translation and bug tracking):</p>

  <img src="/++resource++product_icon.gif" />
  <b>The Ubuntu Distribution</b>
  [<a href="/distros/ubuntu">View</a>]<br />
  Ubuntu uses the Launchpad for all translation and bug tracking.

  <hr />

  <img src="/++resource++product_icon.gif" />
  <b>GnomeBaker - CD Burning Application</b>
  [<a href="/products/gnomebaker">View</a>]<br />
  GnomeBaker is a popular CD burning GUI application for the Gnome desktop
  environment. It uses the Launchpad primarily for translation services
  through Rosetta.

  <hr />

  <img src="/++resource++product_icon.gif" />
  <b>Bazaar - Distributed Revision Control</b>
  [<a href="/products/bazaar">View</a>]<br />
  Bazaar is a distributed revision control system that is based on Arch. It
  uses the Launchpad for bug tracking.

  <hr />

</div>

</body>
</html>
